<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1926-11-19T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1926-11-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="211" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d211">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">868.51ForcedLoan,1926/9</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Greece</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Goold</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Athens</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1926-11-19"><hi rend="italic">November 19,
                                    1926</hi></date>.<lb/>[Received December 2.]</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 669</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: In reply to your instruction No. 357 of
                            October 28th, with reference to the application of the forced loan
                            decree of January 1926, to American consular officers of career, I have
                            the honor to state that I have duly made the prescribed representations
                            to the Foreign Office.</p>
                        <p>In reply to the inquiry as to whether any consular officers other than
                            Mr. Fernald were damaged by the operation of this decree, I have the
                            honor to reply in the negative.</p>
                        <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">H. S. Goold</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>